    <h1>Staff Resources</h1>
<!--    <div class="posted-date">Posted --><!--</div>-->
</div>
<div>
    
<p>The following plan was made with the well-being of ISD students, staff and community in mind.  Our goal is to protect the health, safety, and well-being of our staff, meet the needs of our students and community, while ensuring the financial stability of our employees and the Independence School District.  March 30 through June 30, all sick and personal leave will be considered Paid Time Off (PTO). This allows employees the flexibility to use their leave as needed. </p>



<p><strong>Full-time and part-time certificated teaching staff will continue to receive full pay and benefits while continuing to create lessons for our Virtual Learning Resources.</strong></p>



<p><strong>Regular full-time and part-time hourly employees will need to review the following information and considerations.</strong></p>



<p><strong>As of Monday, March 30<sup>th</sup>, employees who are not part of our Core Operations Team/performing essential duties have the following options: </strong>Employees can perform the duties they have been assigned. This could mean preparing or serving meals, painting or other duties as assigned.</p>



<p>·           Employees can elect to use their PTO</p>



<p>·           Employees can elect to take Leave Without Pay</p>



<p>·           Employees can take a paid furlough (FFCRA full pay for two weeks which can begin on or after April 1). More information on FFCRA can be found at <a href="https://www.dol.gov/agencies/whd/pandemic/ffcra-employer-paid-leave" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">https://www.dol.gov/agencies/whd/pandemic/ffcra-employer-paid-leave</a></p>



<p>·           *If you elect to take the FFCRA furlough, you will be paid to stay home for two weeks and not work. Find more information on <a href="https://www.isdschools.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/FFCRA_Poster_WH1422_Non-Federal.pdf">FFCRA here.</a></p>



<p><strong>As of April 15<sup>th</sup>, employees who are not part of our Core Operations Team/performing essential duties have the following options:</strong></p>



<p>If you took the FFCRA furlough, you must choose from the following:</p>



<p>·           Return to performing duties as assigned. This could mean preparing or serving meals, painting or other duties as assigned.</p>



<p>·           You can elect to use your PTO. Please keep in mind that any choice to utilize PTO can be drawn from the 2019-2020 or the 2020-2021 school year, if you have exhausted existing PTO time.</p>



<p>·           If you have a son or daughter under the age of 18 in your home, you can elect to utilize Emergency Family Leave Medical Act (EMFLA). EMFLA provides two-thirds of your normal pay. If you select this option, you can also opt to utilize your PTO to cover the other one-third of your pay to equal full pay. This option is available up to the end of your contract or for up to 10 weeks (whichever is shorter). If you are currently on FMLA OR have exhausted your FMLA, please contact Human Resources for guidance.</p>



<h2><strong>FAQ</strong></h2>



<p><strong>FFCRA </strong>– Families First Coronavirus Response Act</p>



<p><strong>EPSL </strong>– Emergency Paid Sick Leave</p>



<p><strong>EFMLA</strong> – Emergency Family Medical Leave Act</p>



<p><strong>Does EPSL (paid furlough) and EFML affect my retirement?</strong></p>



<p>If you are taking EPSL or EFML, your retirement will not be impacted. If you take PTO, your retirement will not be impacted. You will continue to pay into retirement and pay for any benefits you have elected beyond the district pay benefits.</p>



<p><strong>How will LWOP impact my evenpay?</strong></p>



<p>Non-exempt 9,
10, 11 month evenpay employees have their dock leave spread out over the remainder
of their evenpay installments.</p>



<p><strong>How will the emergency paid leaves appear on my paycheck?</strong></p>



<p>Employees being
paid EPSL or EFLM will see offsetting docks and pay for these special leave
payments on the same pay period information.</p>



<p><strong>How does EPSL (paid furlough) and EFML affect my benefits?</strong></p>



<p>If you are taking EPSL or EFML, your benefits will not be impacted. If you take PTO, your benefits will not be impacted.</p>



<p><strong>If I have to take leave without pay (LWOP), will this impact my benefits?</strong></p>



<p>LWOP will not impact the <strong>district paid portion</strong> of your benefits. Employees are still responsible for paying employee’s paid portion of any benefits, even when taking LWOP.</p>



<p><strong>If I have to take leave without pay (LWOP), will this impact my retirement?</strong></p>



<p>LWOP will have an impact on service years with retirement for PEERS and PSRS.</p>



<p><strong>Can I work the first week and then take the paid furlough later?</strong></p>



<p>Yes. The EPSL is available from April 1, 2020 through December 21, 2020. A person must continue to meet one of the six qualifications in order to access the EPSL. The leave cannot be taken intermittent. It does have to be consecutive. Qualifications can be found here <a href="https://www.isdschools.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/FFCRA_Poster_WH1422_Non-Federal.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">https://www.isdschools.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/FFCRA_Poster_WH1422_Non-Federal.pdf</a></p>



<p><strong> Are teachers eligible for EFMLA?</strong></p>



<p>Anyone who believes they qualify for EFMLA needs to work with Greg Gilliam. This is a very specific qualification.</p>
